<DOC><DOCNO> AP880430-0128 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 1746EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-JetBlast-Photos     04-30 0231</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Jet Blast-Photos,0236</SECOND><HEAD>Passenger On Ill-Fated Jet Had Camera Ready</HEAD><HEAD>LaserPhotos HU1,2,3,4 and LaserColor HU5</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Jet Blast, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A passenger on the Aloha Airlines jet that blewopen in flight took dramatic photographs of the pilot and co-pilotassisting passengers after the plane's precarious but safeemergency landing.   Robert Nichols, 61, of Kailua, Hawaii, was carrying a camera forbusiness use Thursday on the flight from Hilo, on Hawaii Island, toHonolulu. Nichols, an executive of Tropical Rent-A-Car, said he hadinspected and photographed a building under construction in Hilothat morning.   Nichols said that when he saw the upper fuselage of the Boeing737 blow away, he took a piece of paper from a magazine and beganwriting.   ``I didn't know how long I had,'' said Nichols, but he startedkeeping a log, pouring out his heart to his wife, Jan, for what hewas sure was the last time.   Nichols was uninjured, but after the plane's emergency landingat Kahului Airport, he was held overnight at Maui Memorial Hospitalbecause he is recovering from a heart attack.   Nichols said he was director of Pan American World Airways'training school for flight attendants for 30 years, and had highpraise for the actions of the flight attendants.   Nichols said he met his wife 40 years ago on his first flight asa Pan Am steward. </TEXT></DOC>